Then again, the term σοφιστής is in no sense applicable to Maternus, the poet and pleader, not to mention that it is intrinsically improbable that a man of such idealistic aspirations should sixteen years later have degenerated into a mere school-rhetorician. Finally, the name itself is exceed- ingly frequent. A Curiatius ilfaternus is met with twice in inscrip- tions‚¹⁸³ while Maternus (or Materna), apart from the Spanish jurist so highly complimented by his fellow-townsman, Martial,¹³⁶ and the two well-known Firmici Materni of the 4th century, occurs about 100 times-¹⁸⁷

Maternus is undoubtedly the protagonist of the Dialogue, and may be considered, for the reasons given on p. xxxviii, as in a large measure representing the author’s personal convictions. The scene of the debate is laid in his house. He suggests the preliminary discussion3 directs the course of the conversation, answering for himself and for Secundus (c. 16 8); he suinmarises the arguments of the various speakers (c. 24 1 ff. 33 1 ff.) 3 recalls Messalla to the main theme at issue; requests him to continue, at the same time assigning the particular topic which he desires him to treat.
